// TUNING PARAMETERS:
// EventID values: 4698 (create), 4702 (update), 4699 (delete)
// TaskName patterns: Add other suspicious names based on your environment
// Regex pattern: Adjust length for random string detection
// CommandLine indicators: Add other suspicious PowerShell switches

// NOTES:
// - Scheduled tasks run with SYSTEM privileges (high impact)
// - Attackers use them for recurring malware execution
// - Task names often mimic legitimate Windows tasks for stealth
// - PowerShell with -enc (encoding) = strong indicator of malicious use
// - /S (silent) flag on regsvr32 = DLL execution without UI
// - MSHTA = Microsoft HTML Application execution (fileless attack)
// - Legitimate scheduled tasks usually created by SYSTEM or known admins
// - Review CreatedByAccount - user accounts shouldn't create system tasks
// - Multiple task creation in short time = malware spreading
// - Requires Windows Event Forwarding or Sysmon for reliable detection
// - Can correlate with file creation in Task Scheduler directories
